> When I run a model locally using Ollama command, it always creates a server behind the scenes. Right?

Yes, exactly. Whenever you run a model using ⁠Ollama, it automatically operates as a background server process (using REST API on http://localhost:11434).  
This architectural setup allows local applications or web user interfaces to easily connect and interact with your AI models.  
How it works behind the scenes:  
The Background Daemon: When you start using Ollama, a background service boots up. 
It manages your model memory, loads parameters, and processes prompts.  
API Endpoints: The Ollama API handles requests sent from the CLI or third-party applications.  
It even mimics the OpenAI API structure at /v1/chat/completions,  
So you can drop your local model into code built for OpenAI without changing much.  
Memory Management: If you run multiple different commands (like ollama run llama3), the server keeps the model ready in your RAM.  
After about 5 minutes of inactivity, it will typically unload the model to free up memory for your system.  
If you want, I can help you: Check the status of your background server using your terminal. Set up a graphical chat interface (like Open WebUI).  Connect your running model to your custom code or app.

> Is it possible to stop this backgound serve always I want?

Yes, you can completely stop and disable the background server whenever you want. The method depends entirely on your operating system,  
and you can also prevent it from starting automatically when your computer boots up.  

How to Stop the Server Right 

Now in Windows Systems Tray: Right-click the Ollama icon in your Windows taskbar tray (bottom right corner) and click Exit.  

Command Line (PowerShell): Force kill all instances instantly by running:
```powershell
Stop-Process -Name "ollama*" -Force
```  
macOScMenu Bar: Click the Ollama icon in the top menu bar and select Quit Ollama.  
Terminal: Force quit the process using:  
```bash
pkill ollama
```  

Homebrew (If installed via brew): Stop the background service by running:  
```bash  
brew services stop ollama
```  

Linux:

Systemd: Stop the native background service with:  
```bash  
sudo systemctl stop ollama
```  

How to Prevent Ollama From Starting Automatically:  
If you do not want Ollama to hoard system resources on boot, you can block its auto-start behavior: 
Windows: Open Task Manager (Ctrl + Shift + Esc), click the Startup apps tab, find Ollama, and click Disable.
macOS: Go to System Settings > General > Login Items. Under the Allow in the Background section, find Ollama and switch the toggle to Off.  
Linux: Permanently disable the boot service by running:  
```bash
sudo systemctl disable ollama
```  



